I'm trying to use SignalR. However, I am not sure if it can do what I need it to do.

When setting up SignalR in Startup we have to call the following:

`app.UseSignalR(routes =>
{
    routes.MapHub<Chat>("chat");
});`

Now please think of this scenario, I tried to simplify the scenario as much as I could.

Let's say I go to my website and I open my profile page. That page lists all sort of chat messages that have my name in it. Then I open another tab and go to home page. There I type in the chat my name and send a message. This message will show on my profile page, but then I enter another user and send a message. This second message should not show up on my homepage, it should be on the homepage of that user.

To achieve this, from what I can tell, I have to map 2 hubs. However, I need this for every user and they will register to the site after startup runs. The other part to consider is if let us say this was Twitter. TONS of users. I thought about just filtering the message through javascript and only displaying if it has my name in it on the profile page, but if this is a very heavy hitting website, that is far too much data being sent to every client.

Is limiting what is sent to which client possible? The only way I thought of it was having multiple chat hubs and registering them on startup. More than likely the answer is yes and I did not fully understand the proper use of SignalR. If you could, please point me in the right direction.

Consider the following API:

```C#
public async Task<ActionResult<Contact>> Get(int id)
{
    var contact = await DbContext.Contacts.Where(item => item.ContactId == id).SingleOrDefaultAsync();
    if (contact == null)
    {
        return NotFound();
    }
    
    return contact;
}
```

We could reduce this by assuming ActionResult<T>(null) indicates a NotFoundResult rather than an ObjectResult with a null value (which is what we do now). Resulting code:

```C#
public Task<ActionResult<Contact>> Get(int id)
{
    return DbContext.Contacts.Where(item => item.ContactId == id).SingleOrDefaultAsync();
}
```

